WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.480 --> 00:00:03.300
- I have AI conversations all the time.

2
00:00:03.300 --> 00:00:05.490
At the dinner table, at the grocery store.

3
00:00:05.490 --> 00:00:07.290
I'm only slightly exaggerating.

4
00:00:07.290 --> 00:00:10.680
It feels like everyone
is talking about AI.

5
00:00:10.680 --> 00:00:13.710
You might feel like you need
to become an expert overnight.

6
00:00:13.710 --> 00:00:16.440
But what if I told you
that using AI effectively

7
00:00:16.440 --> 00:00:18.330
has less to do with being a tech genius,

8
00:00:18.330 --> 00:00:21.510
and more to do with understanding
a few simple principles.

9
00:00:21.510 --> 00:00:23.610
Let's start with some
of the things AI can do

10
00:00:23.610 --> 00:00:25.320
and how it can help you at work.

11
00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:28.710
First, AI can help you
understand information.

12
00:00:28.710 --> 00:00:31.080
Think of summarizing
multi-page reports in seconds,

13
00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:32.850
getting insights from a dense spreadsheet,

14
00:00:32.850 --> 00:00:35.700
or getting up to speed
on a client's industry.

15
00:00:35.700 --> 00:00:38.400
This can help set you
up for better decisions.

16
00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:39.930
AI can also create new things.

17
00:00:39.930 --> 00:00:41.490
It can help you draft communications,

18
00:00:41.490 --> 00:00:43.140
build the outline of a presentation,

19
00:00:43.140 --> 00:00:45.510
and even generate product images.

20
00:00:45.510 --> 00:00:49.170
And finally, AI can help
you improve your work.

21
00:00:49.170 --> 00:00:51.000
It can poke holes in a project plan,

22
00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:53.670
or suggest ways to make
a client proposal better,

23
00:00:53.670 --> 00:00:56.820
and it can give you fresh
ideas for you to evaluate.

24
00:00:56.820 --> 00:00:59.010
My team uses AI all the time.

25
00:00:59.010 --> 00:01:01.290
Our job is to create efficiencies

26
00:01:01.290 --> 00:01:03.630
and drive for impact for Google research.

27
00:01:03.630 --> 00:01:06.030
I'm always inspired by the
ideas they come up with

28
00:01:06.030 --> 00:01:08.640
for using AI in our everyday work.

29
00:01:08.640 --> 00:01:11.040
So how do you get AI to work for you?

30
00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:13.350
Good news is if you can give instructions,

31
00:01:13.350 --> 00:01:15.510
you already have some of the skills.

32
00:01:15.510 --> 00:01:18.510
That's because AI
understands natural language.

33
00:01:18.510 --> 00:01:20.370
That means you communicate
through everyday words,

34
00:01:20.370 --> 00:01:23.010
either through typing or through speech.

35
00:01:23.010 --> 00:01:23.843
But if you wanna go

36
00:01:23.843 --> 00:01:26.910
from being a good user to
a really effective user,

37
00:01:26.910 --> 00:01:28.560
there's some technique involved.

38
00:01:28.560 --> 00:01:31.110
Let's talk about some of
the things you need to know.

39
00:01:31.110 --> 00:01:32.940
The key to using AI well

40
00:01:32.940 --> 00:01:36.630
is giving clear and specific
instructions, or prompts.

41
00:01:36.630 --> 00:01:38.850
Prompts are instructions you give to AI

42
00:01:38.850 --> 00:01:41.040
to get the results that you want.

43
00:01:41.040 --> 00:01:42.390
Sometimes you'll upload files

44
00:01:42.390 --> 00:01:43.680
or other documents in your prompt

45
00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:45.600
that you want it to take into account.

46
00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:49.080
Everything you include in your
prompt is called an input.

47
00:01:49.080 --> 00:01:52.500
What AI generates in return
is called the output.

48
00:01:52.500 --> 00:01:53.360
Knowing how to prompt well

49
00:01:53.360 --> 00:01:57.030
is a fundamental skill to
unlock AI's full capabilities.

50
00:01:57.030 --> 00:01:58.530
Because AI is frequently changing,

51
00:01:58.530 --> 00:02:00.360
you might hear about new features, apps,

52
00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:01.740
and models being released.

53
00:02:01.740 --> 00:02:03.840
It can feel like a lot to keep track of.

54
00:02:03.840 --> 00:02:06.150
So let's break down what these terms mean

55
00:02:06.150 --> 00:02:09.840
so you'll know how to leverage
these advancements at work.

56
00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:12.930
First, let's start with
the AI model Gemini.

57
00:02:12.930 --> 00:02:15.570
Think of the model as a
car's engine under the hood.

58
00:02:15.570 --> 00:02:16.440
It's the technology

59
00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:19.440
that does the actual
reasoning and generation.

60
00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:22.110
Even though the engine
provides all the horsepower,

61
00:02:22.110 --> 00:02:24.660
you don't need to
interact with it directly.

62
00:02:24.660 --> 00:02:28.080
So to make use of the
engine, what would you do?

63
00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:30.303
Well, as the driver, you get into the car.

64
00:02:31.170 --> 00:02:35.220
That car is the AI app, and
you're in the driver's seat.

65
00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:39.180
In this course, our home
base will be the Gemini app.

66
00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:40.800
You can access it on your phone

67
00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:44.190
or via the web at gemini.google.com.

68
00:02:44.190 --> 00:02:46.320
Okay, you're in the car.

69
00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:48.780
Now how do you get it to do what you want?

70
00:02:48.780 --> 00:02:50.940
You press the ignition button,
grab the steering wheel,

71
00:02:50.940 --> 00:02:52.410
and push that gas pedal, right?

72
00:02:52.410 --> 00:02:55.590
Well, to command AI, we
use parts of its interface,

73
00:02:55.590 --> 00:02:57.600
like the chat box and its features.

74
00:02:57.600 --> 00:02:59.280
When a new feature's released,

75
00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:01.350
you can go back to the
app and check it out.

76
00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:04.860
But the Gemini models power
more than just the Gemini app.

77
00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:08.130
It's a family of some of
Google's most capable AI models,

78
00:03:08.130 --> 00:03:10.080
and it's built into
products like Google search,

79
00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:11.823
Maps, Pixel, and more.

80
00:03:12.780 --> 00:03:14.250
While you're in the Gemini app,

81
00:03:14.250 --> 00:03:16.440
you can explore different
models and features

82
00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:19.650
to pick the right one for what
you're trying to accomplish.

83
00:03:19.650 --> 00:03:22.140
So what's the best model for your task?

84
00:03:22.140 --> 00:03:24.030
Different AI models have
different strengths,

85
00:03:24.030 --> 00:03:25.470
depending on how they were trained

86
00:03:25.470 --> 00:03:27.720
and how their learning was refined.

87
00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:29.640
Some models are really good

88
00:03:29.640 --> 00:03:32.010
at quickly providing all-around help.

89
00:03:32.010 --> 00:03:34.080
Other models might be
best for advanced tasks

90
00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:35.550
like research, coding,

91
00:03:35.550 --> 00:03:38.350
or weighing the pros and cons
of a complicated decision.

92
00:03:39.270 --> 00:03:43.530
Keep in mind, more complex
tasks require more computations,

93
00:03:43.530 --> 00:03:45.480
which could take the
model longer to complete.

94
00:03:45.480 --> 00:03:47.100
As you use different AI tools,

95
00:03:47.100 --> 00:03:48.210
there are other things you can do

96
00:03:48.210 --> 00:03:50.700
to customize your experience.

97
00:03:50.700 --> 00:03:54.180
For example, Google AI Studio
offers advanced settings

98
00:03:54.180 --> 00:03:56.910
such as temperature, but
temperature in this context

99
00:03:56.910 --> 00:03:59.250
isn't about whether or
not you need a jacket,

100
00:03:59.250 --> 00:04:03.510
it's about controlling the
creativity in AI's output.

101
00:04:03.510 --> 00:04:05.790
A lower temperature
setting means the output

102
00:04:05.790 --> 00:04:08.730
will likely be more
predictable and consistent.

103
00:04:08.730 --> 00:04:09.600
A higher temperature

104
00:04:09.600 --> 00:04:11.550
means you'll get a more inventive output

105
00:04:11.550 --> 00:04:13.740
that could be less predictable.

106
00:04:13.740 --> 00:04:18.180
Remember, AI doesn't know
anything, it's just using its data

107
00:04:18.180 --> 00:04:20.130
and learning to predict what
the best answer might be

108
00:04:20.130 --> 00:04:22.350
from a range of possible options.

109
00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:25.350
Temperature is just one way
to experiment with this.

110
00:04:25.350 --> 00:04:27.950
Okay, it's time to start
putting this into practice.